Customer Success & Retention Services

Which customers are most likely to cancel in the near term?
Those with monthly billing terms (80%+) and women (17.6% more than men).

What behavioral signals appear before a customer cancels?
Past due 21+ days (cancellation rate is is 100% at this point; however, further data validation needed because every customer canceling after 21 days seems unusual), last active 15+ days ago (63.4%+), 9 or fewer days of activity
in the past 30 days (17% higher cancellation than 1-14 days past due), and 4 or more customer support calls (80%+ cancellation).

Which segments should be prioritized for reactive and proactive outreach?
Infrequent users, over 14 days since last activity, high number of customer support calls within the last 30 days.

Marketing / Customer Acquisition & Retention 

What does the highest-value customer profile look like, and how do we keep and attract more of them?
They have been customers for an average of about 48 months with over 1/3 of using their subscription 15-24 days in the last 30 days.
With only 3 support calls in the last 30 days which is the lowest of all segments in this report.
Demographically, they lean male at 60% and the largest age range is 40-64 years old at 47%.

They're equally split between plan types and show no preference for billing terms.

Since this group is based on tenure, 3+ years, and total spend, we don't need to attract them. Instead, 
our focus should be on keeping the customers who have not reached the High-Value status and increasing their spending with us. We do this by 
monitoring accounts with high risk cancellation flags (outlined above and in the report) and taking preventaive
measures like reminders incentives to use our service often and regularly. 

Are there plan types that correlate with long-term retention?

Plan Types: With a cancellation rate range of 56.07% to 58.18% for the 3 plan types, there is no
significant differences between them.

Which customer segments are generating disproportionate support volume?

The Bottom 20%. Over 36% of the customers in this segment made 7-10 calls (data caps at 10 calls) in the last month and this group made ~23% of total support calls. Additionally, then only generate 6.6% of total revenue.
Compare to the Top 20% which made 14% of all support calls but 24% of revenue.

Where can support resources be better allocated or gated?
The Bottom 20%'s access to support resources should be limited or eliminated. Options could include reducing the window of time they can
access support, changing the type of support they receive to a lower cost option (AI, automated, etc.), incentivizing (speed, cost, ease, etc.) DIY resolutions. 
It might make sense to eliminate rention efforts with Bottom 20% accounts that make a high number of support calls, too.

Support resources should be concentrated in the Top 20%, High-Value Customers, which are Top 20% with 3+ years tenure, because they spend more
on average $227 more than the Middle 60%, are more active users than the other segments, and 4+ support calls are coorelated with a higher cancellation rate.

